## Frequently Asked Questions

### Are there any disadvantages to choosing Medicare Advantage?

Yes, there can be disadvantages. Medicare Advantage plans may limit you to network providers, require referrals, or change benefits and coverage options from year to year. You may also pay a monthly premium in addition to Part B coverage. Original Medicare often gives you broader provider access.

### What costs should I expect when enrolling in a Medicare Advantage plan?

You should expect to keep paying your Part B premium, which is tied to Medicare taxes and Medicare coverage rules. Some plans also charge a monthly premium. On top of that, you may have a copay, coinsurance, deductibles, and other health care services expenses depending on the services you use.

### Can I change my plan if my healthcare needs change?

Yes, but only during allowed times. Medicare beneficiaries can usually change plans during the open enrollment period, and some qualify for a special enrollment period. If your doctors leave the network providers list or your coverage options, including Part D coverage, no longer fit, review your next election window carefully.

